"<B>Sonnet 1</B>"
By:  John Sims

What is it that makes the sonnet that is my love spring to life?
What is it that makes me think of houses, children, and a wife?
Spring love has yet to bloom, the frosty chill of winter warms;
Under blankets, wrapped tight in one another's sweet, embracing arms.

What is it that breaks my heart each time we have to part?
What is it that my eyes can say what my mouth can't even start?
Oft times, I wish I could sit and listen to the rain, at your side;
My love, I say, is true to you, in this I do confide.

My dear, my dear, I shant want to part, though sacrifice is paid;
Thought we cannot be every minute together, our love shall not be weighed;
For I love you, whether rain or shine, whether prospered or destitute;
My heart, for you, my very soul, shall I always attribute.

Do not fear, my one, I shall not stray, for you I will true stay;
For you, dearest love, have the love to get me through my days.
